This is a good video showing what a firing line operation on the #ParkFire looks like. One point that Zeke Lunder makes in his commentary on the video (link below) is that the firefighters had to do this in mid-afternoon under dangerous conditions because the fire was bearing down on the road. It would have been vastly preferable to do this as a prescribed burn in the spring when conditions were much less extreme, and it would have been much less likely to lose control of the burn.

“Would you like to do your firing operation in May or would you like to do it on the 30th of July with 100-degree weather and swirly winds?”

An important point is that if we do not proactively perform prescribed burns under favorable conditions (easily controlled and prevailing winds favorable for minimizing smoke exposure), they will eventually be done in much worse conditions as part of an emergency firefighting operation, or the area will burn as part of a wildfire. You can't avoid fire on the landscape; you can only delay it.

"This level of containment means that just 14 percent of the perimeter of the fire has been enclosed by a control line. In other words, most of the fire is burning out of control." ...

UPDATE - Look how the #ParkFire's progress has come to a near screeching halt (red areas are new growth).
FFs have successfully held the 32 (huge victory), they've corralled the area where it punched through the 36, and the only *real* fire activity is where it's skunking around the Mill Creek drainage, where they have the most difficult terrain to manage. 
Much of CalFire's Hail Mary Highway through the wilderness has actually been successfully established, which is kinda mind-blowing. They may pull off the impossible. The efforts that private timberland operators have done over the years laid the foundation for their success, and they've exploited it beautifully. 

HOWEVER, I think it's highly likely that NE edge of the fire will push through that drainage and go farther NE. Weather is un-ameliorating. CalFire has done an absolutely spectacular job of taking advantage of the good weather days to construct a LOT of line, but today we will see an increase in SxSW winds, a decrease in RH, and some potentially double-plus-ungood T-storms will be pushing into CA through the weekend, so there's an increased chance of the fire waking up in the NE corner. The good news? What's to the NE of that fire? The Dixie Fire scar. This thing doesn't really have anywhere to go, given where it's *currently* aligned. 

CalFire is doing their best to try and protect private timberlands, but past fire activity in this area has been largely positive for the ecosystem, so no matter what happens, I'm not alarmed. Might not be a bad thing to see the fire fulfill its destiny up to the 32. 

Now, I keep saying "CalFire", but that doesn't mean you don't have tons of USFS and other agency personnel doing God's work on this fire. This fire started on CalFire dirt, so they're the Unified Ordering Point (UOP). They're in command of the fire, it's their budget, and they have a different mission than the USFS does, and they also have a different culture. I've often noticed that CalFire can be more aggressive with putting fire on the ground than the Feds are comfortable with. There are pros and cons to this. 

Sometimes you put fire down and it rips out of control, or people up the line aren't expecting it...can be bad. But sometimes, that bias for action pays off, and you save millions of acres of timber, houses, and lives. I don't think either approach is the right one, but on this incident, the bias for action in putting fire down along the 32 has been successful and paid dividends. I admire their huevos for doing it, and all the CalFire & USFS operators who pulled it off.

The last few days, the Park Fire has – mercifully – been boring. It's a welcome respite. The biggest risk now, as I've said, is other fires. We have a lightning bust pushing into SoCal starting today, and it will become more widespread moving northward through the weekend...major risk of lots of new starts. As we saw in 2008 and 2020...when you have a lightning bust bringing hundreds of simultaneous ignitions, you simply can't staff every one, and they all go to maximum potential.

Today is day 1 of Dirty August. We are now entering peak fire season. Buckle up.

FWFD Wildland Deployment Update 

[8/3]- As of this morning, the #ParkFire in California is 27% contained with more than 400,000 acres involved. 

The Fort Worth Fire Department Wildland crew arrived Wednesday evening for a 2-week deployment. Currently they are working in the Tehama Zone out of the Red Bluff Camp. This is located at the northern edge of the fire. 

The crew is part of a larger Strike Team. Their primary function is to support heavy equipment, hand crews and other engines within the division with line construction, hose lays and point protection for values at risk. 

The Strike Team (and Division as a whole) have lost a lot of tires due to the  incredibly rough terrain. The days are long, the work is tough but the impact of helping is more than worth it. 

Please continue to keep our crew, all the firefighters and the residents impacted by this historic wildfire in your thoughts and prayers. 

Stay safe, #fortworth.

#ParkFire - some very rugged fellas are punching in handline down the gnarly Mill Creek drainage ahead of the only active fire front (which isn't all that active). One very interesting thing stands out: 
Look how the fire largely bent around the 2012 Mill Fire scar. Wonder if there's a lesson in there?

The existing and upcoming handline is well ahead of this spot fire in the Mill Creek drainage, and in a perfect world, they'll let the fire get there. A little bit of a wind test today, so perhaps it will get there in the next few days. 

We're only looking at maps because that's the only thing to look at. Lookout cameras have all been turned away. The fire pornographers have long been gone, back home waiting anxiously for the next disaster to feast on...all while dozer operators continue pushing iron through the remote forest with a jug of coffee. Hotshots and T2 crews chew through dip and drip drop while they carve through the wilderness. 
It's thankless work buttoning up a fire...especially once the houses have stopped burning and the media no longer cares, but every day there's all the same risk of snags cracking you in the head, the dozer rolling off the craggy ridgeline you've been avoiding all week for good reason...

DROWNING IN KAWARTHA HIGHLANDS SIGNATURE PARK
(MUNICIPALITY OF TRENT LAKES, ON) - Officers from the Peterborough County detachment of the Ontario Provincial Police (OPP) along with EMS and Fire responded to a possible drowning at Kawartha Highlands Signature Park.
On Friday August 2, 2024, just prior to 2:00pm, Peterborough County Officers were dispatched to assist EMS at the Kawartha Highlands Signature Park. Information provided indicated that two friends were drifting in the river on tubes and one person had gone missing from their tube.
Officers arrived on scene along with Fire and EMS and spoke with witnesses. Witnesses advised that two individuals were drifting down the river on tubes. The first person got off their tube in roughly chest high water and was not wearing a life jacket. The second person got off their tube closer to shore and looked back to see the first person gone. The second party was able to locate the others tube but not the person. They attempted to search for the person but were not able to locate them.
Park Wardens were notified and a short while, the first person was located face down in the water.
An 81-year-old male from Whitby was pronounced deceased at the location.

#CoolScience Trees near California’s massive Park fire likely holding their breath

“If you were to suddenly walk into a smoky room, you'd likely instinctively cover your mouth and stop breathing—at least while you find your way to cleaner air. Trees don’t have the luxury of running from smoke, but they do ‘hold their breath’ when exposed to it, researchers have discovered.

While ponderosa pines don’t have lungs, the trees take in carbon dioxide and emit oxygen through small pores in their leaves called stomata—an exchange that researchers liken to breathing. A team of scientists happened to be studying these pores and the compounds going in and out of them in a forest in Colorado in 2020 when smoke from the season’s nasty fires settled in. They were shocked to discover that the trees completely closed their stomata in response, “effectively holding their breath,” they write in a piece for The Conversation.

Ponderosa pines are a common species in the Northern California forest where the Park fire currently rages, so it’s likely that they—and perhaps other plants—are holding their breath in this manner while firefighters try to contain the blaze. Why they might do this isn’t clear. When people breathe in wildfire smoke, the small bits of ash can wreak havoc on their insides . It’s possible these tiny particles harm plants’ internal organs, too.

Whatever the reason the trees stop breathing, with fires increasing in frequency, size, and severity because of climate change, it’s more important than ever to figure out the effects of smoke, the researchers behind the study say.” 

#ScienceAdvisor follow the link to read the paper.

Police Activity Advisory: Overdose at Central Park in Downtown Turlock, Another Arrested on Warrant

At about 4:38pm, Turlock Police and Fire was dispatched to a call of sick person at Central Park, located at S. Golden State Boulevard and E. Main Street.

It was reported someone was turning blue in the face, possibly overdosing.

Upon arrival, units reported that NARCAN was administered.

AMR arrived on scene and transported the patient.

Another person was arrested on a warrant.

Police reported that the patient was the same person who overdosed at the same location last week.

Stay clear of the area if possible and beware of the environment around some the parks and areas seeing an increase in transients and open drug use.

****

Ever since California Governor Gavin Newsom ordered State agencies to start removing homeless encampments from public properties, Turlock has seen an influx of homeless/transients/vagrants - especially back in the Downtown district (where homeless shelters and services are located).

Newsom said that his executive order was in the interest of public health - something Turlockers have been stating and advocating for years in the best interest for our community and citizens (and the transients living in what turns out to be an open-air drug market with garbage spread all over).

Many say that Newsom is just trying to clean up cases of failure that will look bad for Kamala Harris - the Democrat POLITICAL Party’s pick to run for President after Joe Biden was pushed out by the Democrat big donors.

This follows an example of how Joe Biden stopped President Trump’s border policies like “Remain in Mexico,” but then Biden reinstated it back to what Trump had - only after a flood of illegal border crossings from South America came through Mexico and got pushed over into America.

Turlock City News has also received messages about white busses dropping off people at the Lander Avenue Exit, off of Highway 99. We are looking into this as well.

WILDFIRE NEWS ⚠️California's Park Fire Spirals Out of Control: Resources Overwhelmed and Safety Concerns Rise 

California: The Park Fire has escalated dramatically, with multiple reports indicating severe challenges in containment. Numerous resources demobilized today after the fire breached a 16-blade-wide dozer line. Footage shows the intense situation, with another dozer burning and its operator sustaining burns to the face and neck. Multiple crew members also suffered burns while attempting to control the fire.

Initially, suppression repair was the focus, but the current concern is the fire's advance towards Mineral. Despite extensive preparation around the community, the fire's unpredictability has left heavy equipment scattered, and command overhead is reportedly struggling to track resources. Oddly, there was a decision not to burn off the dozer line, even though a head fire was expected to impact it.

The fire, which started under dire circumstances, continues to pose significant challenges. The influx of messages indicates a growing concern that the situation is deteriorating rapidly.

Hey Truckers! Have You Rolled Through the Valley of Fire in Nevada? 

If you haven't yet, you're missing out on one of the most stunning drives in the country! The Valley of Fire State Park, with its vibrant red sandstone formations and ancient petroglyphs, offers a surreal landscape that feels like you're cruising on another planet. The winding roads through the park provide breathtaking views at every turn, making it a perfect detour for those long hauls.

Imagine taking a break from the usual interstate scenery and immersing yourself in the natural beauty of this geological wonder. It's not just a drive; it's an experience that rejuvenates the spirit and adds a dash of adventure to your journey. 

So, next time you're in Nevada, do yourself a favor and take a detour through the Valley of Fire. Your eyes (and your soul) will thank you!

Raging Inferno: Capturing the Heart of California's Park Fire

California: Scenes from inside the Park Fire today… Crews had to pull back and shelter inside vehicles after fire activity increased dramatically. The fire is over 414,000 acres now and about to become the 3rd largest in California’s history.

The dramatic photo captures the intense, fiery essence of the Park Fire near Mill Creek in Tehama County. Towering plumes of thick smoke are set against the backdrop of a clear blue sky, with majestic pine trees standing as silent witnesses to the chaos. Mill Creek is known for its proximity to Lassen Volcanic National Park, where bubbling hot springs and fumaroles tell stories of an ever-active geological past. This region, part of the Lassen National Forest, is rich in natural beauty, with its rugged landscapes and serene waterways like Mill Creek itself, offering a haven for outdoor enthusiasts.

Historically, the area has seen its fair share of natural events, from volcanic eruptions to wildfires, each shaping the land and its communities. As the fire consumes vast swaths of forest, firefighters face unrelenting challenges, battling not only for the land but for the legacy of these ancient woods. Local communities, with their roots deep in the soil of Tehama County, hold on with resilience, much like the towering trees striving to stand tall amidst the onslaught.

As the third-largest fire in California's recorded history, this monumental event reminds us of the delicate balance between nature and human intervention. The image, captured amid these formidable conditions, tells a story that is both heartbreaking and a powerful testament to the enduring spirit of those standing at the frontline.

"El incendio del Parque permaneció activo durante la noche debido a la mala recuperación de la humedad, presentando recorridos cuesta arriba y un comportamiento de fuego intenso. Continuará ardiendo activamente, moviéndose hacia el norte y el este, ascendiendo pendientes con combustible críticamente seco.
Hoy, el humo espeso mantendrá las temperaturas un poco más frías y aumentará la humedad sobre las partes activas del incendio hasta más tarde esta tarde.
Las cuadrillas continúan luchando contra el calor intenso y los drenajes profundos, atacando el fuego de manera ofensiva donde sea seguro hacerlo.
Se han actualizado algunas advertencias de evacuación en el área al este de Mill Creek. La repoblación también se está produciendo en la parte inferior del incendio. Sea diligente ya que hay equipos y equipos trabajando en esas áreas. Manténgase alerta ya que las actualizaciones de evacuación siguen siendo dinámicas", informa el Departamento de Silvicultura y Protección contra Incendios. #cafire #cawx #wildfire #ParkFire

CALIFORNIA FIRES  
Park Fire, the 4th Largest in California History‼️

The Park fire, the largest wildfire currently burning in the United States, has torn through over 426,000 acres in Northern California in recent weeks and has destroyed hundreds of homes and other structures.

The fire ballooned in size in a matter of days, and it is the largest blaze in California so far this year. Thousands of firefighters and other personnel, some from as far as Utah and Texas, are battling the fire, which was 34 percent contained as of Wednesday.

The hot and dry weather has made it difficult for firefighters to suppress the blaze, which is spreading northeast within Lassen National Forest and “ascending slopes with critically dry fuel,” according to Cal Fire. But forecasters say the coming days could bring lower temperatures and higher humidity levels in the fire zone. 

Current unseasonably warm temperatures are expected to steadily fade and give way to highs in the 70s next week.
“It’s not a dramatic change, it’s slow. But each day is getting a little better,” said Eric Kurth, a meteorologist with the National Weather Service office in Sacramento. “That’s certainly helpful.”

There were two new wildland fires confirmed in the Northeast Region by early evening on Thursday, August 8:
Algonquin Park 2 (APK002) is a 0.1 hectare      fire that is out. This fire was located in the southern part of Algonquin      Provincial Park, approximately 21 kilometres west of Maynooth.
Timmins 10 (TIM010) is a 0.1 hectare fire that is not yet      under control. This fire is located on McArthur Lake, approximately      52 kilometres northwest of Matachewan.
At the time of this update, there are 25 active wildland fires in the Northeast Region in various stages of control: 2 are not yet under control, 1 is being held, 3 are under control and 19 are being observed.
The fire hazard is predominantly moderate to high for most of the Northeast Region. Areas north of Blind River to Mississagi River Provincial Park and around Spanish River Provincial Park, Greater Sudbury, Temiskaming Shores and Latchford are under an extreme fire hazard. There is a low fire hazard along the Highway 11 corridor east of Smooth Rock Falls and going north along the James Bay coast. The fire hazard varies from moderate to high along the Hudson Bay coast.

The Park Fire, #California’s largest wildfire of the year, has burned over 660 square miles (1,709 square kilometers) since it began on July 24 near Chico, growing significantly due to hot and dry weather conditions.

As of Thursday, containment of the fire remained at 34%, despite efforts by firefighters to control its spread.
The fire initially became California’s fourth-largest wildfire on record before reduced intensity last week due to favorable weather. However, it has intensified again this week because of heat and low humidity.

While much of the burned area is in the mop-up stage, spot fires continue to pose challenges. The northeast corner of the fire remains the top priority for firefighting efforts.

The fire has destroyed 636 structures and damaged 49 others. A local man has been arrested for allegedly starting the fire by pushing a burning car into a gully.

Resources from the Park Fire are being redirected to combat a new fire in El Dorado County, the Crozier Fire, which has already burned over 2 square miles and threatens 1,625 structures.
Firefighters are using techniques such as drip torches to manage the fire's spread, and officials emphasize the ongoing need for vigilance and hard work in the coming days to prevent further destruction.

On August 9th, 2024, at approximately 4:46 p.m., Collingwood and Blue Mountains OPP, Simcoe County paramedics, and Collingwood Fire and Rescue responded to a call for service off the shore of Sunset Point Park, regarding a young individual that was believed to be drowning.
Collingwood OPP officers with the assistance of two members of the public, were able to successfully rescue the individual and return to shore safely. The individual was assessed by Paramedics and Fire. The individual was transported to Collingwood General Marine Hospital for precautionary monitoring.
At the time of the incident the individual was pulled off the shore due to a strong current and wavy weather conditions. The individual did not have a floatation device on their person and was later discovered to be an inexperienced swimmer.

Isaiah 43:2 - "When you pass through the waters, I will be with you; and when you pass through the rivers, they will not sweep over you. When you walk through the fire, you will not be burned; the flames will not set you ablaze."

In the journey of faith, we navigate through varied landscapes — some lush and serene, others rugged and intense. Isaiah 43:2 brings us a divine promise of presence and protection that transcends all circumstances. It's a reminder that no matter what we face, we are not alone; God is with us, guiding and guarding every step.

This verse is not merely about survival; it's about triumph. It assures us that in God's company, the waters that threaten to overwhelm us become passageways to new strength, and the fires we fear transform into refining experiences that leave us unscathed, shaped, and shining brighter.

Today, let this promise uplift your spirit. Whether you find yourself wading through challenging waters or walking amidst the flames of trial, remember, God's presence is your constant. His strength is made perfect in our weakness, turning our trials into testimonies of His faithfulness.

How Much Would Fuel Reduction Reduce the Intensity of the Park Fire?

We are conducting research where we take conditions over the course of a fire and warm the background climate to see what we expect fire intensities to look like in the future. We also simulate fuel reduction treatments to see how future warming and fuel treatments would simultaneously affect a fire over its lifetime.

Below, this procedure is applied to California's Park Fire. The black line shows the calculated potential for fire intensity over the Park Fire's lifetime (using a weather forecast for a few days in the future). We see tremendous variability driven by changes in weather, topography, and underlying fuels over the course of the fire.

In particular, we see daily peaks in fire intensity as it gets warmer and drier in the afternoon, especially when this coincides with strong winds. Also, the amount of fuel and how dry that fuel is are huge drivers of fire intensity potential.

In addition to the black line, which represents the severity of the Park Fire under today’s climate and fuel conditions, the colored lines represent the same Park Fire progression in 2050 temperature conditions, with and without hazardous fuel reduction.

In 2050, the temperature conditions are about 1.5°F warmer, translating into drier fuels more conducive to higher-intensity fires. The red and magenta lines show the situation without hazardous fuel reduction. We see that the red and magenta Fire Intensity Potential lines are almost universally higher than the black Fire Intensity Potential line, indicating that the warming in the 2050s does increase fire intensity. Sometimes this climate change component is quite large. For example, on August 5th, this increase was about 25% from around 400 to around 500 megawatts. However, hourly and daily weather variability is much larger than this climate change signal.

It is important to note that two different greenhouse gas emissions scenarios are shown. One is a slow emissions reduction scenario that roughly represents current global policies (SSP2-4.5), and one represents fast emissions reductions that are much more aligned with the Paris Agreement (SSP1-2.6). The movement from the slow emissions reduction scenario to the Paris Agreement scenario represents major differences in the global energy and agricultural economies, technology adoption, geopolitics, etc. Yet, these differences translate into only marginal changes in Park Fire’s 2050 intensity.

When it comes to addressing wildfires, greenhouse gas emissions reductions are often heralded as the primary lever we can pull. However, trying to influence weather-related outcomes through energy policy is incredibly indirect and there are often much more direct solutions at hand.

https://t.co/Ec8oDEZPDj

In that vein, the blue line represents the progression of the Park Fire in 2050 under slow emissions reductions (4.5) but with hazardous fuel reduction. Not only is the blue line always below the red and magenta lines, meaning that it would reduce fire intensity over the fire's entire lifetime, but it is also typically below the black line, representing the Park Fire in today’s climate.

This means that even in a situation of 2050 warmth, under a slow emissions reduction scenario, hazardous fuel reduction would reduce the Park Fire’s intensity relative to today.

Brown, P.T., Strenfel, S.J., Bagley, R.B., Clements, C.B. The Potential for Fuel Reduction to Offset Climate Warming Impacts on Wildfire Intensity in California. EarthArXiv [Preprint]. February 21, 2024. https://t.co/6ivP25H2O5
